``` python
class Drop(mx.operator.CustomOp):
    def __init__(self, probs=[0.5,0.5]):
        self.probs=probs    #can be different for each layer
    def forward(self, is_train, req, in_data, out_data, aux):
        if is_train:        #testing is ignored for demo
            options=[0,1]   #0: only identity, 1: summed result
            self.choice=np.random.choice(options,1,p=self.probs)
        if self.choice==0:
            out=in_data[0]
        elif self.choice==1:
            out=in_data[0]+in_data[1]
        self.assign(out_data[0], req[0], out)
    def backward(self, req, out_grad, in_data, out_data, in_grad, aux):
        if self.choice==0:
            out_grad0=out_grad[0]
            out_grad1=0
        elif self.choice==1:
            out_grad0=out_grad[0]
            out_grad1=out_grad[0]            
        self.assign(in_grad[0], req[0], out_grad0)
        self.assign(in_grad[1], req[1], out_grad1)

#usage
output=mx.symbol.Custom(data1=identity, data2=residual, op_type='drop')
```

I find that some works achieve very good results with such drop path technique, such as FractalNet, [resnet of resnet](https://arxiv.org/abs/1608.02908) and another similar method [Swapout](https://arxiv.org/abs/1605.06465).

So I think it will help a lot for mxnet users if we can reproduce their results.
